<a class="definition-word" data-category="general-biology" id="tetracycline_trans_activator_tta">Tetracycline Trans-activator (tTA)</a> - Is a fusion of a tetracycline-destabilising <a href="#dna_desoxyribonucleic_acid">DNA</a> binding domain and the <a href="#vp16">VP16</a> <a href="#tad">trans-activation domain</a>. Thus, in the presence of <a href="#doxycycline_dox">DOX</a> (an analog of tetracycline) tTA can no longer bind to its target <a href="#promoter">promoter</a> - this system is referred to as <a href="#doxycycline_dox">DOX</a>-off because in the absence of <a href="#doxycycline_dox">DOX</a>, it activates <a href="#geneExpression">gene expression</a> at target <a href="#promoter">promoter</a> with tetracycline-responsive elements (TREs).